        {
            "id": "a211987b44594e67889b8",
            "questionText": "Astronauts on the Moon are sending a signal to Mission Control on Earth. Given that the average distance between the Moon and Earth is $!$384{,}400\\ \\text{km}$!$ and that the speed of light is $!$3.00 \\times 10^8\\ \\text{m/s}$!$, calculate the approximate one-way time delay in seconds for the signal.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "31efc998777f46f3b2536",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula needed to determine the light travel time. Please choose the formula that relates time to distance and speed.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "50d7e88d-ebc2-4bb8-a6d9-a4634fe1e452",
                        "613636b3-0ae8-4a7d-b7b3-a3b03cbc9952"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$t = \\frac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{speed}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$t = \\frac{\\text{speed}}{\\text{distance}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$t = \\text{distance} \\times \\text{speed}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "0c8a04e16fae4fc98bb24",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, we need to ensure that the units are consistent. Convert the given distance from kilometers to meters. (Remember: $!$1\\ \\text{km} = 1000\\ \\text{m}$!$)",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "384400000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "0a80b00a38294eec84d91",
                    "stepText": "Now that we have the distance in meters, use the formula identified earlier to compute the one-way time delay by dividing the distance by the speed of light.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.28"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "seconds",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "50d7e88d-ebc2-4bb8-a6d9-a4634fe1e452"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "0545b9a3f01e4b0ea01ca",
            "questionText": "A group of amateur astronomers is tracking the phases of the Moon throughout 2024 from the Northern Hemisphere. They know that the Moon orbits Earth in approximately $!$27\\text{ days}$!$, and that a New Moon was observed on January 1st, 2024. Assuming the year has $!$365\\text{ days}$!$, compute the total number of First Quarter Moons that could be observed in 2024.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "ee1b68450f4248259e35a",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by confirming the Moon's orbital period. Identify the value that represents the Moon's orbital period from Earth in days.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "0d016f00-77a7-4749-8c3f-0d07898d933c"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "Approximately $!$27\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Approximately $!$30\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "Approximately $!$20\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "bfc97325546d47d8a0f7e",
                    "stepText": "Now, calculate the total number of lunar cycles in 2024 by dividing the total days in the year by the lunar orbital period. Compute $!$365/27$!$ and determine the whole number part of the cycles.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "13"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "cycles",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "9914f09f78ea414c92367",
                    "stepText": "Next, determine the remaining days in 2024 after accounting for the complete lunar cycles. Subtract the days used by the full cycles from the total days (i.e., compute $!$365 - (13 \\times 27)$!$).",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "14"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "days",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "deef5fcaa8564458a439f",
                    "stepText": "Now, consider the time needed in a lunar cycle to reach the First Quarter phase. Identify the formula that represents the time required to reach the First Quarter from the New Moon phase.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "96d513e0-02bf-40d5-942e-7876926b2086"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Time} = \\frac{27}{4}\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Time} = \\frac{27}{3}\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\text{Time} = \\frac{27}{2}\\text{ days}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "243360bd88a64284b5b8d",
                    "stepText": "Finally, determine the total number of observable First Quarter Moons in 2024. Add the number from full lunar cycles to an additional one if the leftover days are sufficient for a First Quarter phase to occur.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "14"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "phases",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
